H2O Notes:

     The H2O channel was not measuring ambient during the intervals listed
in the previous discussion.

Comparison with MR:

     The trends in XMRLI mirrored those of MR, however, during many flights
an offset was observed to occur between the values of the two sensors.
Typically the water mixing ratio measured by the LI-COR was higher.  The
table below lists the mean offset for each flight.

             Flight      Mean difference (g/kg)
                           (XMRLI - MR)
                1              0.3
                2              0.3
                3              2.4
                4              2.0
                5              1.0
                6              1.3
                7              1.8
                8              1.0
                9              0.5
                10             0.5
                11             0.6
                12             0.2
                13             0.5
                14             0.2
                15             0.4
                16             0.5
                17             3.6
                18             2.8
                19             3.3
                20             2.5
                21             1.9
                22             1.6
                23             2.4
                24             0.6
                25             1.8

Recommendations:

     Much has been learned about the behavior and drawbacks of using the
LI-COR CO2/H2O analyzer for aircraft measurements.  However, some issues
remain unresolved.  In spite of modifications to the pressure correction of
ambient data, a residual pressure/altitude effect remains.  This effect is
variable and seems at first glance to be affected by the calibration factor
and drift, as well as by the offset and offset drift.  Additionally, the
effect of changing water mixing ratio on the measured CO2 concentration
needs to be characterized or water removal from sampled air needs to be
effected.

     Apparently, the instrument performed well enough during this project
(818) to produce flux measurements of reasonable quality.  However, the data
should be used with extreme caution for evaluation of mean levels, and for
comparison of measurements as a function of altitude.  Clearly, further
development effort needs to be undertaken before this instrument is
supported for airborne CO2 measurements.


15.  Data Quality Report by Richard Schillawski on the RAF fast ozone
     instrument.  Data processing algorithms, including temperature
     correction, are provided for each of the intensive periods.

Fast (NO Chemiluminescence) Ozone

     Variables List:  XO3F1S; XO3F1P; XO3F1N; XO3F1F; XO3F1T.

The fast ozone instrument is based upon the reaction of nitrogen oxide (NO)
with ozone (O3).  The reaction produces light principally in the infrared;
a small portion of the light produced can be detected by the red-sensitive
photomultiplier tube (PMT) used as the measuring device by this instrument.
This method is also used in the reverse direction in most instruments
measuring low concentrations of nitrogen oxides in the atmosphere.  The
flow rate of sample gas through the fast ozone instrument is kept high to
be useful in eddy-correlation flux estimates where a response rate of at
least 10 Hz is desired.  The signal level is also relatively large in the
fast ozone instrument;  the PMT voltage can be measured directly, rather
than by photon counting which is usual in nitrogen oxides analyzers.

For the BOREAS project, two fast ozone instruments were operated in
parallel to compare their performance.  The unit whose output was used to
produce the derived variable XO3FC uses dry ice cooling;  the other unit
uses refrigeration.  The refrigerated unit was coupled with a different
reactor for each of the BOREAS intensives:  during the first intensive its
reactor was nearly identical to that used on the dry ice-cooled unit;
during the second, a slightly smaller reactor of the type commonly used for
high-sensitivity nitrogen oxides detection was used;  and during the third
intensive a much smaller reactor which is usually used for "semi-fast"
ozone measurements by RAF was used.  The signals from the refrigerated
system are intended for RAF in-house use only.

Fast ozone data quality was generally good throughout the BOREAS project
with the following exceptions:  during the first four flights of the
project, a bad input card in the aircraft data system (ADS) added noise to
the PMT signals from both fast ozone units (XO3F1S and XO3F2S);  reactor
temperature control was not very good through much of the project, but a
correction for variation in reactor temperature has been added to
compensate for this problem in producing the calibrated ozone data.  The
data from the slower ozone instrument suffered from aerosol effects, which
were unexpectedly large during the BOREAS project, and its calibrated
output (TEO3C) should be used with caution.

The calibrated fast ozone output (XO3FC) was calculated by comparison with
the slow ozone data (TEO3C), with provision made for the effect of aerosols
on the latter.  As mentioned above, an adjustment for reactor temperature
was also made.  The standard algorithm used to produce XO3FC includes a
correction for the effect of humidity upon the amount of light produced by
the reaction, and is

     XO3FC(ppbv) = F1*XO3F1S*(1+3.43*EDPC/PSFDC)

where EDPC is the partial pressure of water (gas phase) and PSFDC is the
total static pressure outside the airplane.  The temperature-correction
factor by which the right side of the standard algorithm was multiplied for
the BOREAS project is

     (1-(XO3FT-F2)*F3).

The constants F1, F2, and F3 were adjusted for each of the intensive
periods as follows:

     Intensive      Flights   F1        F2        F3
     1              1-8       10.0      40.0      0.0184
     2              9-16      11.07     37.0      0.0148
     3              17-24     12.1      37.0      0.0148
     3              25        12.6      37.0      0.0148

16.  Data recording typically begins well in advance of the actual aircraft
     takeoff time.  Virtually all measurements made on the Electra require
     some sort of airspeed correction, or the systems are simply not active
     while the aircraft remains on the ground.  Typically the data
     recording was allowed to continue during stops.  None of the data
     collected while the aircraft is on the ground should be considered
     valid.


